05626nam a22006615i 9781501716034DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017160347 a10.1515/97815017160342doi  a(DE-B1597)571793  a(OCoLC)1253312920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGV838.53.S85bB88 2021 7aARC0100002bisacsh04a797.2009747/12231 aButtenwieser, Ann L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Floating Pool Lady :bA Quest to Bring a Public Pool to New York City's Waterfront /cAnn L. Buttenwieser. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b4 maps, 24 color plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcronyms and Abbreviations -- tMembers of the Floating Pool Crew -- tMap 1. New York City and New Jersey’s Hudson River Waterfront. Courtesy of William Nelson. -- tPrologue: Swim, Annie, Swim! -- t1. Fire and Water -- t2. The Eureka Moment -- t3. Waterfront in Despair -- t4. Hoboken Ho -- t5. Finding the C500 -- t6. Contracts and Crawfish -- t7. Kafka on the Pier -- t8. Perspective Matters -- t9. The Orwellian Bureaucracy -- t10. The Big Jump -- t11. The Lady Moves to the Bronx -- tEpilogue: Swim, New York City’s Children, Swim! -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note from the Author -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tKey to map 2, the floating baths, page 22 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy on earth would anyone want to float a pool up the Atlantic coastline to bring it to rest at a pier on the New York City waterfront? In The Floating Pool Lady, Ann L. Buttenwieser recounts her triumphant adventure that started in the bayous of Louisiana and ended with a self-sustaining, floating swimming pool moored in New York Harbor.When Buttenwieser decided something needed to be done to help revitalize the New York City waterfront, she reached into the city's nineteenth-century past for inspiration. Buttenwieser wanted New Yorkers to reestablish their connection to their riverine surroundings and she was energized by the prospect of city youth returning to the Hudson and East Rivers. What she didn't suspect was that outfitting and donating a swimming facility for free enjoyment by the public would turn into an almost-Sisyphean task. As she describes in The Floating Pool Lady, Buttenwieser battled for years with politicians and struggled with bureaucrats as she brought her "crazy" scheme to fruition. From dusty archives in the historic Battery Maritime Building to high-stakes community board meetings to tense negotiations in the Louisiana shipyard, Buttenwieser retells the improbable process that led to a pool named The Floating Pool Lady tying up to a pier at Barretto Point Park in the Bronx, ready for summer swimmers.Throughout The Floating Pool Lady, Buttenwieser raises consciousness about persistent environmental issues and the challenges of developing a constituency for projects to make cities livable in the twenty-first century. Her story and that of her floating pool function as both warning and inspiration to those who dare to dream of realizing innovative public projects in the modern urban landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic bathszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aSwimming poolsxSocial aspectszNew York (State)zNew York. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aUrban Studies. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aUrban waterfront planning, new york city history, Manhattan waterfront, bronx waterfront.  anew york city waterfront, Baretto Point Park.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete